<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="49">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">New to Norway, Sweden and Austria.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vain. ex H. Magn" authorityYear="1935" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Acarosporaceae" genus="Sarcogyne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sarcogyne hypophaeoides" order="Acarosporales" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="hypophaeoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">Sarcogyne hypophaeoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has until now been known from the type material in central Finland and from one collection in Germany (
<bibRefCitation author="Magnusson, AH" journalOrPublisher="Kryptogamen-Flora von Deutschland, Oesterreich, und der Schweiz" pageId="24" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 318" refId="B48" refString="Magnusson, AH, 1935. Acarosporaceae, Thelocarpaceae. Kryptogamen-Flora von Deutschland, Oesterreich, und der Schweiz 5 (1): 1 - 318" title="Acarosporaceae, Thelocarpaceae." volume="5" year="1935">Magnusson 1935</bibRefCitation>
). It is a characteristic but overlooked lichen that appears to be widespread in Scandinavia. The apothecia are 0.5-1.2 mm wide, with a reddish brown to almost black disc sometimes with a central carbonized accretion. The margin is typically finely striated (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Sarcogyne hypophaeoides. a Apothecia (S F 123697) b Apothecia (Kocourkova &amp; Hafellner 46366 (GZU )) c Section of an apothecium showing a carbonized margin and a brownish black hypothecium (S F 265197). Scale: 1 mm (a-b); 100 µm (c)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64937" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">12a, b</figureCitation>
) and is softer and more leather-like in texture and not as strongly carbonized and brittle as the margin in e.g., 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. clavus" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="clavus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">S. clavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The degree of carbonization varies however and in sections the central parts of the exciple may be rather weakly coloured (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Sarcogyne hypophaeoides. a Apothecia (S F 123697) b Apothecia (Kocourkova &amp; Hafellner 46366 (GZU )) c Section of an apothecium showing a carbonized margin and a brownish black hypothecium (S F 265197). Scale: 1 mm (a-b); 100 µm (c)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64937" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">12c</figureCitation>
). The hymenium is 70-90 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
tall and has a euamyloid reaction (I+ blue) and the spores are narrow and almost bacilliform, 3.5-5.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Acarosporaceae" genus="Sarcogyne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sarcogyne hypopaheoides" order="Acarosporales" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="hypopaheoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">Sarcogyne hypopaheoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can mainly be confused with 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. clavus" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="clavus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">S. clavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. hypophaea" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="hypophaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">S. hypophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has a dark, brownish black to black hypothecium (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Sarcogyne hypophaeoides. a Apothecia (S F 123697) b Apothecia (Kocourkova &amp; Hafellner 46366 (GZU )) c Section of an apothecium showing a carbonized margin and a brownish black hypothecium (S F 265197). Scale: 1 mm (a-b); 100 µm (c)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64937" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">12c</figureCitation>
), which is a characteristic and diagnostic feature of this species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krempelhuber" authorityYear="1861" baseAuthorityName="DC." class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Acarosporaceae" genus="Sarcogyne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sarcogyne clavus" order="Acarosporales" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="clavus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">Sarcogyne clavus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very uneven, cracked, crenulate margin and a yellowish to pale brown hypothecium. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arnold" authorityYear="1870" baseAuthorityName="Nyl." class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Acarosporaceae" genus="Sarcogyne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sarcogyne hypophaea" order="Acarosporales" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="hypophaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="49">Sarcogyne hypophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the other hand, has a smooth margin, which usually appears segmented due to 2-3 deep incisions in the margin and a colorless hypothecium.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973722" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64937" pageId="16" pageNumber="49" start="Figure 12" startId="F12">
